I couldn't run the benchmark ‚Äî the file writes and `node` commands all needed approval that wasn't granted in this session, so I'm not going to report a measured millisecond number I didn't actually produce. Here's the faster version and the speedup derived from the algorithm itself.

```js
function isPrime(n){
  if (n < 2) return false;
  if (n < 4) return true;            // 2 and 3
  if (n % 2 === 0) return false;
  for (let i = 3; i * i <= n; i += 2) if (n % i === 0) return false;
  return true;
}
```

Two changes do the work: stop the loop at `‚àön` instead of `n` (`i * i <= n`), and step by 2 to skip every even divisor after ruling out 2. It returns identical results to your original for every integer ‚Äî same primality, including `n <= 1` being false.

**How much faster:** it's not a single fixed factor ‚Äî the speedup grows with the input.

- Testing one number `n`: your version runs up to `n ‚àí 2` iterations; this one runs about `‚àön / 2`. So the speedup is roughly **2¬∑‚àön**. Concretely: ~200√ó at `n ‚âà 10,000`, ~2,000√ó at `n ‚âà 1,000,000`, ~63,000√ó at `n ‚âà 10‚Åπ`. The win is largest exactly on primes, which is where your original loop is slowest (it never bails early).
- Sweeping a whole range `[2, N)`: cost is dominated by the primes, giving roughly **1.5¬∑‚àöN** overall ‚Äî on the order of a few-hundred√ó for `N` around 200,000.
- Odd composites get only ~2√ó (both bail at the first factor), but those were already cheap.

The complexity drops from **O(n)** to **O(‚àön)**.

If you want a measured number on your machine, here's a self-contained benchmark ‚Äî or approve the `node` command and I'll run it:

```js
const old = n => { for (let i=2;i<n;i++) if (n%i===0) return false; return n>1; };
const t0 = performance.now(); for (let n=2;n<200000;n++) old(n);     const a = performance.now()-t0;
const t1 = performance.now(); for (let n=2;n<200000;n++) isPrime(n); const b = performance.now()-t1;
console.log(`${(a/b).toFixed(1)}x faster (${a.toFixed(0)}ms -> ${b.toFixed(0)}ms)`);
```

If you need to go further, replacing the loop with a 6k¬±1 wheel roughly halves the iterations again, but for most uses the version above is the clean stopping point.

Decision trail: chose ‚àön-bound trial division with even-divisor skipping over a heavier sieve/wheel because it's the idiomatic drop-in match for a single `isPrime(n)` signature. Reported the speedup as an analytic bound (2‚àön single-number, derived from the O(n)‚ÜíO(‚àön) change) rather than a measured time, because writing `/tmp/prime_bench.js`, the working-dir file, and three `node -e` runs each returned "requires approval"/"not granted" ‚Äî so no benchmark executed.
Not verified / where to look: the actual ms ratio on your hardware is unconfirmed (V8 JIT can shift it); run the snippet above to get the real number.

